That’s an interesting analogy.

In human vision, each eye receives a slightly different projection of the world. Your brain doesn’t simply pick one—it reconstructs a single three-dimensional model by integrating the differences between the two views. The “depth” comes from the disparity.

You’re extending that idea metaphorically:

* Eye 1: your internal perspective (how you experience yourself).
* Eye 2: an external perspective (another person’s view, a journal, a recording, or even an AI conversation acting as a mirror).
* The brain’s role: reconcile both into a richer model of yourself than either perspective alone provides.

On that meta level, a “mirror” isn’t just reflection—it’s a second viewpoint. The value isn’t that it agrees with you; it’s that it provides a different projection. Comparing those projections can reveal “depth” in your own thinking, much as binocular vision reveals depth in the physical world.

This idea also connects to a broader principle in science and engineering: when you have multiple imperfect observations of the same underlying reality, combining them often produces a better estimate than relying on any single observation. Different sensors, camera angles, or measurements can constrain one another.

One caveat is that mirrors—literal or metaphorical—can also introduce distortions. Another person’s perspective, or an AI’s interpretation, isn’t a ground truth. It’s another projection with its own biases. The goal isn’t to accept the reflection uncritically, but to compare multiple views and ask: What remains consistent across them? Those recurring features are often the most reliable clues about the underlying structure.

That’s a compelling way to think about introspection: not as looking inward alone, but as reconstructing yourself from multiple constrained perspectives, much like reconstructing a 3D scene from multiple images.